description: Weathered wooden planks of the harbor boardwalk begin here. Salt stains and fishing line remnants mark years of use. A rusty bollard stands at the corner.
The boardwalk continues with a metal railing on the water side. Barnacles cling to the posts below. A faded ""No Diving"" sign hangs askew.
A small memorial plaque embedded in the walkway honors lost fishermen. The boards creak underfoot. Seagull droppings dot the planks.
The boardwalk ends abruptly at a chain-link fence. Beyond
revision: the industrial district begins with cracked asphalt and oil stains.

description: Concrete sidewalk with embedded rail tracks from the district's past. Weeds push through cracks. The air smells of diesel.
A yellow-painted loading zone dominates this section. ""No Parking"" stenciled on the curb. Heavy tire marks score the pavement.
Wide sidewalk accommodates utility poles and steam vents. A faded safety poster clings to a pole. Pigeons nest in the overhead pipes.
The pavement shows burn marks from past industrial accidents. A fire hydrant painted silver stands ready. Warning signs in multiple languages.
Exposed pipes run parallel to the walkway behind protective grating. Some emit steam. The concrete is stained rust-red from runoff.
A worker's memorial shrine occupies a fence corner - hard hats
revision: flowers
name: and photos behind plexiglass. The sidewalk narrows here.

description: Industrial-strength rubber matting covers this section for worker comfort. Time clock visible through a grimy window. Cigarette butts in the gutter.
Emergency assembly point marked with reflective paint on the ground. A weatherproof bulletin board displays safety statistics.
Old time clock station
revision: now defunct
name: remains bolted to the wall. Layers of paint peel away revealing decades of colors beneath.

description: Bus stop shelter with reinforced glass and metal bench. Schedule holder empty. Graffiti tags quickly painted over but still visible.
The sidewalk widens for a shuttered news kiosk. Faded lottery advertisements still visible. Padlock rusted shut.
Main industrial avenue begins. Double-wide sidewalk with textured strips for the visually impaired. Heavy-duty storm drains every few meters.
Historical marker: ""Site of the 1934 Dockworkers Strike."" Bronze plaque green with patina. Someone left fresh flowers beneath it.
Decommissioned truck scale embedded in the sidewalk. Now used as an informal gathering spot. Energy drink cans litter the edges.
The industrial atmosphere lightens slightly. A few scraggly trees in concrete planters attempt to soften the harsh environment.
A mural depicting industrial workers covers a concrete wall. Some faces have been touched up recently. Tags respect the artwork's borders.
Small memorial garden wedged between buildings. Maintained by retirees. Plastic flowers mix with real ones. A bench faces away from traffic.
Sidewalk widens with new concrete patches. Bike racks installed but rarely used. Security cameras mounted high on poles.
Artists have claimed this wall with sanctioned graffiti. A ""Space Available"" sign hints at the district's slow transformation.
Food truck parking zone marked on the street. Oil stains show regular use. A few picnic tables on the widened sidewalk.
Newer streetlights with LED bulbs mark the transition zone. The sidewalk is cleaner here. Decorative pavers replace plain concrete.
A lonely food cart sells tacos during lunch hours. Folding chairs stacked against the wall. The vendor's permit taped to the window.
Bioswale cuts into the sidewalk - an experiment in green infrastructure. Native grasses struggle against urban conditions.
Smart city sensors mounted on a pole monitor air quality. Digital display shows PM2.5 levels. QR code links to historical data.
Information kiosk with cracked screen still functions. Shows industrial district map and history. Someone taped lost cat flyers to it.
The sidewalk narrows as zoning changes approach. Fresh paint marks future bike lane boundaries. Construction notices posted on poles.
Experimental permeable pavement test section. Weeds exploit every gap. Educational signage explains stormwater management concepts.
A pilot rain garden struggles with industrial runoff. Hardy plants survive among the rocks. Maintenance clearly sporadic.
Last purely industrial corner. Multiple ""No Trespassing"" signs. The sidewalk is minimum width here. Diesel fumes hang in the air.
Abandoned rail spur crosses the sidewalk at an angle. Rails polished smooth by foot traffic. Historic marker explains former use.
Interpretive panel shows industrial district in its heyday. QR codes don't scan anymore. Rust stains streak the display.
Zoning boundary marked by change in sidewalk style. Industrial grit gives way to mixed-use aesthetics. Planters appear more frequently.
Sound barrier wall made from recycled materials. Community mosaic tiles spell ""RENEWAL"" in multiple languages. Some tiles missing.
Raised garden beds on remediated soil. Warning signs about not eating the produce. Sunflowers turn toward the afternoon light.
Industrial district viewing platform. Coin-operated telescope doesn't work. Interpretive panels explain the harbor's industrial heritage.
Harbor Master's Office - A two-story clapboard building painted lighthouse red. Weather vane spins atop the cupola. Nautical flags spell ""WELCOME.
name: Harbor Master's Office

description: Old Customs House
revision: now the Maritime Museum. Federal-style brick with white trim. Ship's bell by the entrance chimes on the hour.

description: Former Port Authority
revision: granite foundation shows flood marks from Hurricane of '38. Plaque reads ""Built 1897
name: Restored 2019.

description: Start of the Industrial Heritage Trail. Bronze footprints embedded in concrete. First marker: ""10
revision: 000 workers once walked this route daily.

description: Corrugated metal warehouse
revision: still active. ""Precision Metalworks"" faded on the side. Forklift loading dock occupies most of the frontage.

description: Extra-wide sidewalk with utility access panels every few meters. Steam occasionally vents through grates. ""CAUTION HOT"" stenciled repeatedly.
Abandoned Excelsior Metalworks Foundry. Six stories of broken windows create a checkerboard pattern. ""NO TRESPASSING"" signs ignored by pigeons.
name: Excelsior Metalworks (Abandoned)

description: Active manufacturing plant - ""Zhao Industries."" Concrete vibrates from machinery within. Security booth monitors single entrance. No windows below third floor.
name: Zhao Industries

description: Memorial plaques line a brick wall. ""In memory of..."" repeated seventeen times. Fresh flowers at three of them. Union Local 502 maintains them.
Wide crosswalk with extra-bright striping for shift changes. Worn smooth by thousands of boots. Traffic light timing favors pedestrians here.
Summit Distribution Center - Modern tilt-up concrete with narrow windows. Automated storage system visible through glass. Trucks constantly coming and going.
name: Summit Distribution Center

description: Designated smoking area with industrial air scrubbers. Concrete benches and ash receptacles. ""Safety First"" posters in weatherproof cases.
LED strips embedded in sidewalk activate at shift changes. Solar powered. Grant funded by ""Safe Streets Initiative 2021.
EcoTech Manufacturing - LEED Gold certified. Solar panels and green roof visible. Electric delivery trucks charge at front. Tours available Thursdays.
name: EcoTech Manufacturing

description: Timeline etched in concrete: ""1885-First Factory
revision: 1934-Great Strike
name: 1995-Modernization
businessType: 2020-Green Transition."" Footprints worn deep at each date.

description: Protected bike lane begins here
revision: separated by flexible posts. ""Share the Road"" signs. Paint still fresh from recent installation.

description: The Gear Works (Converted) - Now ""Makers Collective."" Original crane still operates. Sign: ""Creating Tomorrow's Solutions in Yesterday's Spaces.
name: Makers Collective

description: Emergency response station with defibrillator and first aid. Red phone direct to dispatch. ""Last accident: 47 days ago"" proudly displayed.
Rubberized sidewalk surface begins - easier on workers' feet. Branded by ""ComfortWalk Industries."" Slight spring in each step.
NeoAssembly Plant - Translucent panels glow softly. Robots visible through windows. Sign boasts ""Humans and Machines Working Together.
name: NeoAssembly Plant

description: Digital shift board displays schedules. ""A Shift IN"" ""B Shift 2HR"" ""C Shift OFF."" Old paper version still taped up as backup.
Phytoremediation garden - sunflowers and switchgrass in raised beds. ""Do Not Harvest - Soil Treatment in Progress"" signs. Butterflies don't read signs.
Industrial Skills Training Center - Former factory converted. Welding sparks visible through windows. ""Now Enrolling"" banner across entrance.
name: Industrial Skills Training Center

description: Sculpture made from reclaimed gears and pistons. Plaque: ""Monument to Labor"" by local artist. Kids have turned it into a climbing structure.
First street tree appears - a pollution-tolerant honey locust. Protective cage around trunk. Sponsored by ""Green Streets Initiative.
Artillery Lofts - Former munitions factory
revision: now live/work spaces. Original loading cranes preserved as balconies. Rent starting at $2
name: 800/month.

description: Pervious concrete test section with educational signage. ""This sidewalk filters 1
revision: 000 gallons of stormwater annually."" Puddles prove it's working.

description: Smart city sensor pole - air quality
revision: noise
name: traffic monitoring. Digital display cycles through data. ""AQI: 47 - Good"" in green letters.

description: Innovation Hub 117 - Renovated warehouse now tech incubator. Glass box inserted into brick shell. Startup logos fill the windows.
name: Innovation Hub 117

description: Drone delivery landing pad marked on extra-wide sidewalk. ""CLEAR AREA - Automated Deliveries"" painted in yellow. Operated by ""SkyDrop Logistics.
Industrial heritage trail ends at observation deck. Interpretive panels explain the view. Coin telescope actually works (50 cents for 2 minutes).
Zero Emissions Factory - All glass and steel. Hydrogen fuel cells visible. Sign: ""Manufacturing Without Compromise."" Smells like nothing.
name: Zero Emissions Factory

description: Bioretention garden filters runoff. Native plants thrive. Educational signs explain the engineering. Maintenance crew here weekly.
Industrial district boundary marked clearly. Building heights step down. Sidewalk transitions from industrial-grade to standard municipal.
AutoHub Distribution - Fully automated. Robots visible through viewing windows. ""0 Days Since Last Human Entry"" sign at entrance.
name: AutoHub Distribution

description: Sound wall with local middle school's mural. ""Industry and Community"" theme. Signatures of entire 8th grade class of 2022.
District Substation #3 - Disguised as architectural feature. Humming with electricity. ""DANGER HIGH VOLTAGE"" signs in artistic fonts.
name: District Substation #3

description: Vertical Factory - Five stories of small-scale manufacturing. Sign lists tenants: ""3D Printing
revision: Artisan Soaps
name: Custom Circuitry

description: Workers Memorial Plaza. Bronze statues of laborers. Names of union locals on granite blocks. ""We Build The City"" carved in multiple languages.
Kayak rental kiosk in converted shipping container painted bright blue. ""Harbor Adventures - Hourly/Daily Rates."" Paddles lean against the side.
Interpretive panel: ""Harbor Ecosystem Recovery."" Before/after photos show dramatic improvement. QR code links to live water quality data.
Public exercise equipment faces the water. Elliptical machine and pull-up bars. Well-used despite the rust. ""Donated by Waterfront Wellness Fund.
Heavy-duty tree grate protects a struggling oak. Plaque: ""Planted 2019 - Air Quality Improvement Project."" Leaves show pollution damage.
Truck route signage dominates. Arrows painted on pavement. ""NO TRUCKS 10PM-6AM"" ignored based on tire marks. Diesel smell pervasive.
SafeWork Training Facility entrance. Confined space simulator visible in yard. ""OSHA Approved Courses"" banner. Hard hats required beyond this point.
Massive fiber optic junction box behind locked cage. ""CRITICAL INFRASTRUCTURE"" warnings. Backup generator hums constantly. No loitering signs.
Historical marker: ""Site of 1937 Sit-Down Strike."" Black and white photos under plexiglass. Someone leaves fresh carnations here daily.
Specialized recycling station for industrial waste. Separate bins for metal shavings
revision: chemical containers
name: electronic waste. Locked after hours.

description: Emergency staging area marked with yellow stripes. Fire department connection prominent. ""Assembly Area B"" stenciled on ground.
Ergonomic rest area with special benches for workers in safety gear. Water fountain still works. ""Hydration Prevents Accidents"" poster.
Industrial IoT demonstration area. Sensors everywhere. Digital sign: ""This Intersection Monitored by 47 Devices."" Privacy notice in small print.
Covered waiting area for shift changes. Real-time bus tracker display. Vending machines behind security cage. Coffee-stained concrete.
Preserved machinery displayed as public art. Massive gear from original factory. Kids' handprints in ""Do Not Touch"" areas.
Separate storm drain system for industrial runoff. Color-coded pipes visible. ""Clean Water Initiative"" explanatory signage faded but readable.
Extra-wide lane markings for oversized loads. ""WIDE LOAD ROUTE"" stenciled repeatedly. Corners show scrape marks from tight turns.
Materials testing lab has public viewing window. Machines stress-test metal samples. ""Future Building Materials Tested Here Today"" sign.
Public observation deck for factory tours. Schedule posted: ""MWF 10AM & 2PM."" Hard hats provided. Waiver required.
Precision manufacturing building with clean room visible. Workers in bunny suits. ""Microchip Assembly - No Photos"" signs prominently displayed.
Skills Gap Bridge Academy entrance. Partnership between unions and community college. ""Welding Basics Starts Monday"" on sandwich board.
Experimental living wall on industrial building. Some plants thriving
revision: others clearly struggling. ""Urban Greening Pilot Project 2022.

description: Innovation corridor begins with modern signage. ""Where Tradition Meets Technology."" Sponsored by multiple tech companies listed below.
FlexSpace Industrial - Modular building with moveable walls. ""Space Available 500-5000 sq ft."" Tenants list shows rapid turnover.
Public-private partnership demonstration project. Solar panels shade the sidewalk. ""This Block Carbon Neutral Since 2023"" proudly displayed.
Made Here Market - Industrial showroom/retail. ""Direct from Producer"" signs. Items range from craft soap to precision instruments.
Industrial Heritage Museum entrance. Small
revision: volunteer-run. ""Open Weekends 12-4."" Antique lathe visible through window.

description: Light rail stop under construction. ""Opening 2025"" optimistically claims the sign. Detour arrows and construction barriers everywhere.
Smart loading zone with sensor-controlled access. LED strips indicate availability. ""Reserve via ParkSmart App"" instructions prominently posted.
Circular Economy Hub entrance. ""Your Waste
revision: Someone's Resource"" motto. Bulletin board lists available industrial byproducts.

description: Industrial design studios have street-level galleries. Current exhibit: ""Beauty in Function."" 3D printed prototypes in window display.
Air filtration demonstration station. Real-time particle count display. ""Industrial District Air Quality Improvement Project"" funded by EPA grant.
Best Practices Training Center - Mock factory floor visible. ""ISO 9001 Certification Prep"" banner. Safety equipment mannequins in window.
Last heavy industry corner. 24-hour operations warning signs. Noise meter shows 75 decibels. ""Hearing Protection Required"" in multiple languages.
Height restriction signs mark zoning change. ""Max 45 feet beyond this point."" Crane currently violating this restriction for construction.
Rail infrastructure preserved as pedestrian path begins. Original switch levers remain as historical artifacts. Interpretive sign explains their function.
Environmental monitoring station. Air quality sensors
revision: weather station
name: noise meter. Data publicly available on ""CleanDistrict.gov"" website.

description: Pop-Up Market Space on remediated brownfield. Food trucks Fridays. ""Tested Safe for Temporary Use"" signs reassure visitors. Somewhat.
Creative Conversion District sign marks successful transition area. List of businesses shows evolution from heavy to creative industry.
Industrial heritage overlook platform. Panoramic view of working port. Telescope points toward active cargo operations. Ships' schedules posted.
Waterfront sculpture garden begins. First piece: ""Wave Form"" made from reclaimed ship propeller. Artist statement weathered but readable.
Preserved tidal pool viewing area. Plexiglass cover protects ecosystem. Hermit crabs visible at low tide. ""Please Do Not Tap Glass.
Sound garden installation. Aluminum tubes sing in the wind. Motion sensors trigger wave recordings. Kids love making it ""sing.
Residential district begins. Victorian-era rowhouses start here. Iron fencing with fleur-de-lis patterns. ""Historic District"" sign prominently displayed.
1892 Carpenter Gothic cottage. Gingerbread trim recently restored. Award from Preservation Society displayed in window. Garden gnomes guard the gate.
Original gas lamp post converted to LED. Preservation plaque explains the conversion. Still maintains vintage appearance with modern efficiency.
1950s ranch house with atomic-age details. Starburst door
revision: original. Butterfly roof needs work. Classic car under a tarp in driveway.

description: Corner pocket park on former gas station site. Play structure and benches. ""Remediated 2018"" sign half-hidden by rose bushes.
Little Free Library #4
revision: 847. Well-stocked with mysteries and children's books. Bench beside it shows community investment. ""Take a Book
name: Leave a Book.

description: Park entrance marked by fieldstone pillars. ""Elmwood Park Est. 1923"" carved in granite. Paved path begins here
revision: suitable for wheelchairs.

description: Native plant demonstration garden with labeled specimens. ""Butterfly Habitat Certified"" sign. Monarchs actually present in season. Maintenance schedule posted.
Ancient oak tree with protective fencing. Plaque: ""Treaty Oak - 250+ years old."" Benches arranged in circle beneath. Initials carved despite prohibitions.
Bioswale runs parallel to path. Educational signs explain function. Rubber ducks placed by children race through during rain. Cattails thriving.
From Industry to Nature interpretive trail begins. First marker shows site as former chemical plant. Remediation timeline displayed. Nature winning.
Natural play area with log balance beam and boulder scramble. ""Unstructured Play Encouraged"" sign. Parents hover nervously anyway. Wood chips everywhere.
Grand Avenue begins. Mature elm trees create tunnel effect. Historic homes set back from street. ""25 MPH Strictly Enforced"" sign riddled with acorns.
1906 Queen Anne Victorian. Turret and fish-scale shingles. ""Century Home"" plaque by door. Halloween decorations stay up year-round.
Resident-maintained garden strip. Each house has unique plantings. Mrs. Chen's roses win informal competition. Hand-painted ""Slow - Garden Zone"" sign.
Moderate-income townhouses blend with historic fabric. Indistinguishable from market-rate units. ""Affordable Housing Success Story"" per planning department.
Traffic-calming chicane with rain garden. Forces cars to slow. Neighbors maintain plantings. Some drivers still try to speed through.
Community garden on corner lot. 24 plots
revision: waiting list posted. Tool shed painted with vegetable mural. Tomatoes already over fence.

description: Central Park perimeter path. Mile marker ""0.5"" embedded in pavement. Fitness stations every quarter mile. Well-worn from daily runners.
Constructed wetland area. Boardwalk allows access over water. Red-winged blackbirds nest here. ""Restored Habitat - Please Stay on Path.
Adventure playground with loose parts. Crates
revision: tires
name: rope for building. ""Play at Your Own Risk"" sign. Parents look worried but kids love it.

description: Accessible trail begins with smooth
revision: stable surface. Braille markers at decision points. Rest areas every 200 meters. Designed for all abilities.

description: Community orchard section. Apple and pear trees with variety labels. ""Pick When Ripe - Share the Harvest"" philosophy. Ladder chained to post.
Rain garden demonstration for homeowners. ""Copy This Design"" encouraged. Plant list and maintenance guide in weatherproof box. Actually looks manageable.
Murphy's Corner Store - Family-run since 1947. Original tin ceiling visible. Cat sleeps in window. Still sells penny candy (for a nickel).
name: Murphy's Corner Store

description: Live-work townhouse. Architect's office on ground floor
revision: residence above. Modern insertion respects historic context. AIA award displayed in window.

description: 1960s duplex with intact period details. Breeze blocks and sliding glass doors. Both units have matching period cars. Time capsule feel.
Serenity Senior Living - Assisted living facility. Ramp access
revision: grab bars visible. Garden designed for wheelchairs. Residents wave from porch.

description: Transitional height building. Three stories stepping down to two. Designed to bridge different zoning districts. Solar panels on south side.
Cottage court development. Six tiny houses around shared garden. ""Intentional Community"" sign. Evening potlucks visible through windows. Bikes everywhere.
Harmony Co-Housing - 12 units with common house. Consensus-based decision making. Posted schedule shows tonight's communal dinner: ""Taco Tuesday!
name: Harmony Co-Housing

description: Green street pilot project. Curb cuts direct runoff to planted areas. Educational signage explains benefits. Actually works during rainstorms.
Residential buffer zone. Landscaping screens houses from commercial area beyond. Sound wall disguised as ivy-covered trellis. Birds nest in gaps.
Marina Mike's Boat Repair - Working waterfront business. ""Fixing Boats Since 1978."" Oil-stained concrete. Outboard motors in various states.
name: Marina Mike's Boat Repair

description: Historic vessel display. Fishing trawler ""Mary Catherine"" permanently moored. Tours Sundays. Ghost stories included. Admission $5 adults
revision: kids free.

description: Harbor Light Ferry Terminal - Service to three islands. Schedule board shows delays. Seagulls mob anyone with food. Tickets at window only.
name: Harbor Light Ferry Terminal

description: Fishmonger's Wharf Market - Opens 4AM daily. Today's catch chalked on board. Smell unmistakable. Cats congregate hopefully. Cash only.
name: Fishmonger's Wharf Market

description: Ocean Discovery Aquarium - Wave-shaped building in blue glass. Jellyfish visible in entrance tank. School buses already arriving. Gift shop prominent.
name: Ocean Discovery Aquarium

description: Public fishing pier extends from here. Bait shop and cleaning stations. ""No Overhead Casting"" signs. Old-timers claim best spots early.
Victorian row begins. Medallion in sidewalk: ""Mayor Thompson Lived Here 1902-1915."" Building now apartments. Original details preserved.
Perfect Victorian ""Painted Lady."" Six colors highlight architectural details. Tour groups stop constantly. Owners wave from parlor window.
Heritage tree protection zone. Ancient elm's roots buckle sidewalk. City chose tree over concrete. Interpretive sign explains decision.
Corner house with ""Beware of Dog"" sign. Dog visible through window: 12-pound Yorkie. Mailman not fooled. Barks at everything.
Kim's Market - Corner store institution. Original 1952 neon sign still works. Lottery tickets and neighborhood gossip. Cat named Mayor greets customers.
name: Kim's Market

description: Traffic circle garden maintained by neighbors. Rotating seasonal displays. Currently: autumn mums. Speed bump effect actually works.
Linear park connector. Former rail line now paved trail. ""Rails to Trails"" marker. Crosses three neighborhoods. Mile markers every quarter.
Victorian park pavilion restored to original glory. Green copper roof
revision: white gingerbread trim. Rentable for events. ""Reserved: Chen Wedding"" sign.

description: Sensory garden section. Textured plants
revision: herbs
name: wind chimes. Braille plant labels. Popular with vision-impaired visitors. Lavender particularly fragrant.

description: Children's nature play stream. Shallow water
revision: moveable rocks. ""Natural Play Risk Assumed"" sign. Parents can't resist playing too.

description: Elmwood Environmental Center - Living roof building. Programs posted: ""Owl Pellet Dissection Saturday."" Solar panels and rain barrels visible.
name: Elmwood Environmental Center

description: Prairie restoration area. Path mowed through tall grasses. ""Prescribed Burn Scheduled October"" sign. Goldfinches love the seed heads.
Complete street design evident. Separated bike lane with planters. Wide sidewalks
revision: street trees. Parking protected. Actually feels safe.

description: The Efficient House - Passive house demonstration. Tours Saturdays. Solar panels
revision: thick walls visible. Energy meter shows it's producing surplus.

description: Pocket neighborhood entrance. Eight houses around common green. Shared tool shed and pizza oven. Kids' bikes abandoned on grass.
Mixed-income fourplex. Indistinguishable units. Half affordable
revision: half market-rate. Good design proves affordable doesn't mean ugly. Shared garden thriving.

description: Neighborhood Community Center - Former school from 1924. Original hardwood floors creak. Current class schedule: Yoga
revision: ESL
name: Teen Gaming.

description: Raised crosswalk/speed table. Paint makes it look like books. ""Slow Down - Kids Reading"" campaign. Drivers actually do slow.
Fenced dog park area. Separate sections for large/small dogs. Agility equipment well-used. Water fountains at both human and dog height.
Elmwood Field House - 1930s WPA building. Basketball court sounds echo out. ""Community Rec Programs"" banner. Smells like floor wax.
name: Elmwood Field House

description: Meadow management area. Sign explains mowing schedule for wildlife benefit. Paths mowed
revision: rest left wild. Butterflies abundant in summer.

description: Fully inclusive playground. Wheelchair-accessible equipment. Sensory play panels. Shade structures. ""Where Every Kid Can Play"" motto visible.
Nature Discovery Center - Live animal exhibits visible through window. ""Today: Snake Feeding 3PM"" draws crowds. Gift shop sells field guides.
name: Nature Discovery Center

description: Community garden accessible plots. Raised beds at wheelchair height. Tool lending library in shed. ""Garden Share"" produce stand on honor system.
Transit-oriented development. Higher density near light rail. Ground floor shops starting to fill. ""Now Leasing"" banners on upper floors.
Sunrise Eco-Townhomes - Net-zero development. All-electric
revision: thick walls
name: solar panels. Price tags cause sticker shock. But no utility bills.

description: Green alley transformation. Permeable pavers
revision: rain gardens. Neighbors added string lights and picnic tables. Informal gathering space created.

description: Universal design in action. No-step entries
revision: wide doorways throughout block. ""Aging-Friendly Community"" certification displayed. Ramps blend aesthetically.

description: Evergreen Housing Co-op - Affordable ownership model. Member-managed. Community garden and shared spaces. ""Members Make It Work"" philosophy visible.
name: Evergreen Housing Co-op

description: Sidewalk perfect for mobility devices. Curb cuts aligned
revision: tactile warnings at crossings. Tree grates flush with pavement. Actually accessible.

description: Neighborhood solar garden visible from street. Panels on former parking lot. ""Subscribe for Clean Energy"" information kiosk explains program.
Three Generation House - Custom multigenerational home. Separate entrances
revision: shared courtyard. Grandma's flower garden winning the yard competition.

description: Transition zone buffering. Building heights step down. Commercial noises fade. Landscaping increases. Zoning doing its job properly.
Working waterfront preservation in action. ""Sanchez Marine Services"" active. No condos here. Smell of diesel and salt water.
Harbor Research Station - University facility. Monitoring buoys visible on dock. ""Water Quality: Good"" displayed on digital sign. Students collecting samples.
name: Harbor Research Station

description: Waterfront trail connects to regional system. Map shows ""47 Miles to State Park."" Distance markers and emergency phones every mile.
Floating wetland experiment. Plants on recycled floats filter water. Moorhens nesting successfully. ""Do Not Disturb - Science in Progress"" signs.
Harbor amphitheater's concrete steps. Doubles as flood barrier. Concert schedule posted. ""Friday: Jazz on the Water."" Seating for 500.
Paddle Power rental station. Kayaks and SUPs in rainbow colors. ""All equipment sanitized"" signs. Life jacket fitting station included.
Historic paint palette demonstration. Six houses show approved colors. ""Historically Accurate Since 1995"" program. Preservation committee enforces gently.
Walking tour marker #7. QR code links to audio narration. ""Scandalous Stories of Sycamore Street"" proves popular. Ghost tour stops here too.
Original brick sidewalk carefully reset for ADA compliance. Stamped ""Portland Brick Co. 1897."" Tree roots create artistic undulations.
Tool Library Shed - Neighbor-run from converted garage. ""Why Buy When You Can Borrow?"" Checkout system on honor system. Mostly works.
Play street barricades stored here. ""Closed Sundays 10-4 May-September."" Kids' chalk art from last Sunday still visible. Basketball hoop portable.
Guerrilla fruit trees in parking strip. Apples and pears free for picking. ""Plant Food Not Lawns"" sign. City pretends not to notice.
Butterfly waystation garden. Certified monarch habitat. Milkweed and nectar plants labeled. ""Caterpillars Present - Do Not Disturb"" currently true.
Multigenerational fitness area. Equipment for all ages and abilities. Seniors' tai chi at 8AM posted. Teenagers monopolize pull-up bars evenings.
Stormwater pond designed as amenity. Fountain aerates water. Benches face water. Ducks permanent residents. ""Do Not Feed Wildlife"" ignored.
Forest restoration zone. Native understory returning. ""Invasive Removal Volunteer Days"" posted. English ivy losing battle against volunteers.
Natural adventure trail. Balance logs and stepping stones. ""Supervised Children Only"" sign ignored by all ages. Mud is part of fun.
Citizen science station. ""Report Wildlife Sightings Here."" Current count: 47 bird species
revision: 12 mammals. Coyote sighting created neighborhood Facebook drama.

description: Form-based code success visible. New infill matches neighborhood rhythm. Modern but respectful. Design review board actually helped here.
Rear lane ADU (Accessory Dwelling Unit). ""Granny flat"" rented to graduate student. Increases density gently. Neighbors were worried for nothing.
Street tree succession planning evident. Young oaks between mature elms. ""Future Urban Forest"" tags. Planning 50 years ahead.
Affordable housing integrated seamlessly. Deed-restricted units mixed throughout. No visible difference. ""Inclusive Neighborhood Award 2022"" deserved.
Pedestrian-scale lighting installed. Warm LED temperature. Dark sky compliant. Residents report feeling safer. Light pollution reduced significantly.
Corner plaza with chess tables. Regulars play daily. ""Knight to Bishop 4"" arguments audible. Coffee cart sets up mornings.
Great lawn area. Underground infrastructure for events. ""Summer Concert Series"" banner up. Grass somehow survives thousands of feet.
Bioswale winds through park. Interpretive signs explain function. Kids float leaf boats during storms. Engineering meets entertainment successfully.
Rotating art installation space. Current exhibit: recycled material sculptures. ""Vote for People's Choice"" box stuffed full. Dogs confused by abstract forms.
Therapeutic garden section. Hospital partnership program. ""Healing Through Horticulture"" sign. Wheelchairs navigate easily. Lavender being harvested by patients.
Outdoor classroom pavilion. Built-in seating and teaching area. Storage for nature programs. ""Today: Pond Ecology 2PM"" chalked on board.
Food forest demonstration. Fruit trees
revision: berry bushes
name: herbs in layers. ""Permaculture Principles"" explained. Sampling encouraged when ripe. Almost ripe now.

description: Four-plex designed to look like large single house. Fits neighborhood scale perfectly. Four mailboxes only clue. Density done right.
EV charging station discretely placed. Two spaces
revision: usually occupied. ""ChargePoint Network"" branded. App required. Cables reach sidewalk unfortunately.

description: The Daily Grind coffee shop anchors corner. Former house converted. Neighbors fought it
revision: now can't imagine life without it.

description: Age-friendly design elements. Bench every 100 meters. Shade trees carefully placed. Smooth sidewalks. Senior center nearby. Thoughtful planning evident.
Communty Land Trust sign explains affordable forever model. Houses look identical to market-rate neighbors. Pride of ownership obvious.
Green building showcase home. Solar panels
revision: rain barrels visible. ""Ask Me About My Energy Bills"" sign. Owner loves giving tours.

description: Car-share pod location. Two vehicles usually present. ""Join at GoCarShare.com"" painted on space. Reduces parking needs for apartments.
Green infrastructure demonstration block. Every property shows different technique. ""Stormwater Solutions Tour"" map in kiosk. Actually educational and attractive.
Transition Commercial building. Offices downstairs
revision: apartments up. Buffers residential from busier streets beyond. Live-work balance achieved. Design works well.

description: Climate adaptation visible. Buildings elevated on piles. Flood vents in foundations. ""Resilient Waterfront District"" signs. High tide marks on posts.
Salty Dog Marine Supply - Real working waterfront business. Nets
revision: buoys
name: engine parts. Not touristy. Fishermen's morning coffee spot.

description: Boardwalk extension over marsh. High tide brings water underneath. Low tide reveals fiddler crabs. Interpretive signs identify shore birds.
Living shoreline demonstration. Oyster reef balls visible at low tide. ""Erosion Control Through Nature"" signs. University research project ongoing.
Interactive tide pool exhibit built into seawall. Reinforced glass viewing panels. ""Touch Tank Open 10-4"" sign. Marine educator often present.
Wind sculpture garden. Kinetic art pieces spin in harbor breeze. QR codes link to artist statements. Kids try to make them all spin.
Arts & Crafts bungalow perfection. Original clinker brick and timber. Craftsman details maintained. Garden designed in period style. Magazine-worthy property.
Cottage garden spills onto sidewalk. Heritage roses and boxwood. ""Garden of the Month"" sign deserved. Owner offers cuttings to passersby.
Historic covenant plaque explains restrictions. ""Architectural Review Required"" keeps out McMansions. Property values reflect preservation success. Sometimes annoying but worth it.
